result.execSummary:
The defendant Robert S. Engebretson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/Intent-THC (<=200 grams) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime, Possession with Intent to Deliver/Distribute a Controlled Substance On or Near a School], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(h)1.
  • Maintain Drug Trafficking Place [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.42(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Counts 4 and 5 concurrent with each other with the following conditions:

120 days conditional jail time, with work release and stayed until on or before December 2, 2015 between 6-7 a.m.  Jail may be served in any Wisconsin county jail that will accept.  Defendant to report first to the Richland County Jail before requesting that transfer.

Attend, pay for, and successfully complete any educational or treatment programs ordered by the agent.

Submit to AODA and follow through with all recommendations.

Pay court costs and costs of supervision.

Submit DNA sample at the Richland County Sheriff's Department before signing up for probation.

Credit in the event of revocation:  2 days.

Defendant Robert S. Engebretson in court with attorney Peter A. Bartelt. Prosecuting Atty Jennifer M. Harper appeared for State of Wisconsin.  Counsel inform the Court that the parties have reached an agreement for resolution calling for 4 years probation on a withheld sentence for counts 4 and 5.  While counsel are in agreement on the length of probation, they are not in agreement on the length of proposed conditional jail time.  Each argue their positions to the Court on that matter.  Court will order 120 days conditional jail time.  Sentence:  Withheld for 4 years with 120 days conditional jail time (may be served in any Wisconsin county jail, with work release); attend, pay for, and succ. complete any educational or treatment programs ordered by agent; submit to AODA and follow through; pay costs.  Firearm and other felony admonishments given.  Submit DNA sample before leaving the courthouse today.  Stay of conditional time granted - jail not to begin until on or before December 2, 2015 between 6-7 a.m.; report to Richland County first.  Credit in the event of revocation:  2 days.  Counts 4 and 5 and all conditions, including conditional jail time, are concurrent with each other.
